<paper id="1580181578"><title>Efficient Sharing of Many Secrets</title><year>1993</year><authors><author org="UNIVERSITÀ DI SALERNO" id="1854929514">Carlo Blundo</author><author org="UNIVERSITÀ DI SALERNO" id="1931511623">Alfredo De Santis</author><author org="UNIVERSITÀ DI SALERNO" id="54027764">Ugo Vaccaro</author></authors><n_citation>48</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1479821208</reference><reference>1529027305</reference><reference>1590395676</reference><reference>1873063140</reference><reference>1990304797</reference><reference>2080975816</reference><reference>2088023978</reference><reference>2093673286</reference><reference>2099000090</reference><reference>2159401786</reference></references><venue id="1178070762" type="C">Symposium on Theoretical Aspects of Computer Science</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-56503-5_68</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.40731">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.6268">Secure multi-party computation</keyword><keyword weight="0.62111">Secret sharing</keyword><keyword weight="0.42168">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.42819">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Proactive secret sharing</keyword><keyword weight="0.66462">Verifiable secret sharing</keyword><keyword weight="0.64979">Homomorphic secret sharing</keyword><keyword weight="0.54344">Access structure</keyword><keyword weight="0.40364">Distributed computing</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>A multi-secret sharing scheme is a protocol to distribute n secrets s1,..., sn among a set of participants \(\mathcal{P}\) in such a way that: 1) any non-qualified subset of participants \(A \subseteq \mathcal{P}\) has absolutely no information on the secrets; 2) any qualified subset can recover all the secrets, but 3) any non-qualified subset knowing the value of a number of secrets might have some information on other secrets.</abstract></paper>